constructor and destructor in inheritance 
_______________________________________________________

In Python, constructors (__init__) and destructors (__del__) behave differently 
in inheritance compared to some other languages like Java or C++.

Constructor in Inheritance (__init__())
Key Points:
When a subclass is instantiated, Python first calls the constructor of the subclass.

To explicitly call the parent constructor, use super().__init__() or ParentClass.__init__(self).

If super().__init__() is not used, only the constructor of subclass is executed.




 Destructor in Inheritance (__del__())
Key Points:
Destructor is called when an object is about to be destroyed.

Python automatically calls destructors in the reverse order of construction — child first, then parent.

You can explicitly call the parent class’s __del__() from the subclass destructor.


